<div class="prose">

<p><strong>Languages:</strong> தமிழ் (Tamil) · हिन्दी (Hindi) · Français · 한국어 (Korean) · 日本語 (Japanese).</p>

<p>Keep this document open while you read course material. Look up unfamiliar terms in your first language; learn the English terms over time. The visual cues and sentence frames help you USE each term, not just translate it.</p>

<h2>How to use this reference</h2>

<p>Each term has the same five elements:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>English term</strong> — the heading.</li>
  <li><strong>Definition</strong> — a student-friendly explanation in plain English.</li>
  <li><strong>Visual cue</strong> — a suggested image or diagram to help you picture the concept.</li>
  <li><strong>In a sentence</strong> — an example sentence showing how to USE the term in context.</li>
  <li><strong>5-language translations</strong> — starting reference in Tamil, Hindi, French, Korean, Japanese.</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">📌 IMPORTANT — about the translations</div>
  <p>These translations are <strong>AI-assisted starting references</strong>. They help you orient quickly to unfamiliar English vocabulary in your first language. They are NOT verified by native-speaker linguists or technical translators.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use the translation to UNDERSTAND a term — but then practice using it in English (the academic + assessment language).</li>
    <li>Some terms (OPVL, IPCC, op-ed) are commonly used as loanwords across languages — translation marked as loanword.</li>
    <li>If a translation seems wrong or has a better alternative in your dialect, ask Mr. Ignash or a native-speaking teacher. Errors are expected; corrections are welcome.</li>
    <li>For high-stakes work (citations, formal writing), verify against authoritative sources in your language (textbooks, government documents).</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<p><strong>Organization:</strong> Terms are grouped by unit (U0 through U7), in roughly the order they appear in the unit. <strong>Length:</strong> ~140 terms total. Don't try to memorize everything — use the reference as a working dictionary. <strong>Search:</strong> Use Cmd+F (Mac) / Ctrl+F (Windows) to find a specific term.</p>

<p><strong>Jump to a unit:</strong> <a href="#u0">U0</a> · <a href="#u1">U1</a> · <a href="#u2">U2</a> · <a href="#u3">U3</a> · <a href="#u4">U4</a> · <a href="#u5">U5</a> · <a href="#u6">U6</a> · <a href="#u7">U7</a></p>

<h2 id="u0">Unit 0 — Scientific Practices &amp; Class Foundations <span style="font-weight:400;color:var(--muted);font-size:14px;">(15 terms)</span></h2>

<h3>OPVL</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A framework for evaluating sources: Origin, Purpose, Value, Limitations. The four questions you ask of any source before trusting it.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> Four-quadrant diagram showing O / P / V / L as the four corners of a square.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Before citing this article, I'll apply OPVL — first its Origin, then its Purpose, then what it's good for, then what it can't tell me."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>மூலம், நோக்கம், மதிப்பு, வரம்புகள் (loanword OPVL commonly used)</td><td>मूल, उद्देश्य, मूल्य, सीमाएँ (loanword OPVL commonly used)</td><td>Origine, But, Valeur, Limites (anglicisme OPVL souvent utilisé)</td><td>출처, 목적, 가치, 한계 (영어 OPVL 그대로 사용 가능)</td><td>出典・目的・価値・限界（OPVLという略語をそのまま使うことが多い）</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Source</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Any piece of information you cite or learn from — a book, article, website, person, AI output, image, dataset.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A document with an arrow pointing to a student reading it.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "My main source for this claim is a peer-reviewed paper from 2023."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>ஆதாரம் / மூலம்</td><td>स्रोत</td><td>source</td><td>출처 / 자료</td><td>出典・情報源</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Primary source</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A first-hand source — the original document, original research, or direct testimony — not a summary or interpretation by someone else.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A 1923 newspaper photograph vs. a 2025 article that quotes from it.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "For the 2015 floods, the IMD rainfall data is a primary source; the Wikipedia article is a secondary source."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>முதன்மை ஆதாரம்</td><td>प्राथमिक स्रोत</td><td>source primaire</td><td>1차 자료 (primary source)</td><td>一次資料</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Secondary source</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A source that summarizes, analyzes, or interprets primary sources. Useful for context but should be cross-checked.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A textbook chapter that cites many original research papers.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "I started with a secondary source to understand the topic, then went to primary sources for the specific numbers."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>இரண்டாம் நிலை ஆதாரம்</td><td>द्वितीयक स्रोत</td><td>source secondaire</td><td>2차 자료 (secondary source)</td><td>二次資料</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Evidence</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Information that supports a claim. Strong evidence is specific, well-sourced, and relevant to the exact claim.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> An arrow from data → claim. "This data supports this claim."</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "The evidence for human-caused climate change comes from temperature records, ice cores, and atmospheric CO₂ measurements."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>ஆதாரம்</td><td>साक्ष्य</td><td>preuve / élément de preuve</td><td>증거</td><td>証拠</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Argument</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A claim plus the reasoning and evidence that supports it. An argument is more than an opinion — it gives reasons.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A claim with multiple lines connecting it to supporting evidence.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Her argument is that the Cooum should be restored because it would reduce flooding — and she supports this with engineering studies."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>வாதம் / விளக்கம்</td><td>तर्क</td><td>argument</td><td>주장 / 논증</td><td>主張・議論</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Hypothesis</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A testable prediction about what will happen, based on prior knowledge. Different from a guess — must be possible to prove wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> An "if … then …" sentence with a question mark over it.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "My hypothesis is that if rooftop solar is mandated, Chennai's grid stress in summer will decrease."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>முதலியக்கருத்து / கருதுகோள்</td><td>परिकल्पना</td><td>hypothèse</td><td>가설</td><td>仮説</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Observation</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Something you directly see, measure, or detect. Different from interpretation (what you think it means).</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> Eye looking at a phenomenon, with a note: "what I see" not "what I think it means."</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "My observation: the river is darker now than in 2010 satellite images. My interpretation: this suggests increased pollution."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>கண்காணிப்பு</td><td>अवलोकन</td><td>observation</td><td>관찰</td><td>観察</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Inference</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A conclusion you draw based on observation + reasoning. Inferences can be strong (well-supported) or weak (jumping to conclusions).</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> Observation → arrow → conclusion (with a question mark over the arrow asking "is this jump justified?").</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "From the riverbed evidence, scientists infer that Mars once had liquid water."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>ஊகம் / அனுமானம்</td><td>अनुमान</td><td>inférence</td><td>추론</td><td>推論</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Bias</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A systematic preference for or against something that affects how a source presents information. All sources have some bias; the question is which kind and how much.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A scale tipped toward one side, labeled with the source's likely interest.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "The coal industry's report has a bias toward downplaying air-quality impacts."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>சார்பு / பாரபட்சம்</td><td>पूर्वाग्रह / पक्षपात</td><td>biais</td><td>편향</td><td>バイアス・偏り</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Citation</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A reference to where information came from. Includes author, date, title, and where to find the source.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A footnote symbol attached to a sentence.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Every claim in my Source Dossier needs a citation showing where the evidence came from."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>மேற்கோள் / குறிப்பு</td><td>उद्धरण / सन्दर्भ</td><td>citation / référence</td><td>인용 / 참고문헌</td><td>引用・参考文献</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Hallucination (AI)</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> When an AI confidently invents information that isn't true — like a citation, a statistic, or a date. AI doesn't know it's hallucinating.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> An AI speech bubble with sparkles and a question mark — looks real but is fake.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "The AI told me a specific 1923 quote that doesn't exist anywhere — a hallucination I caught when I checked the original source."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>AI கற்பனை / பொய் தகவல்</td><td>AI द्वारा गढ़ी गई जानकारी / भ्रम</td><td>hallucination (de l'IA)</td><td>환각 (AI가 만들어낸 거짓 정보)</td><td>ハルシネーション（AIによる虚偽情報）</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Disclosure</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Telling people honestly that you used a particular tool, source, or assistance. In this class: required for any AI use.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> An open book with the cover labeled "I used AI" — transparent, not hidden.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Honest disclosure of AI use doesn't lower your grade; hiding AI use is an integrity violation."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>வெளிப்படுத்துதல் / அறிவித்தல்</td><td>खुलासा करना / प्रकटन</td><td>divulgation / déclaration</td><td>공개 / 공시</td><td>開示・公表</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Documentation</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Recording what tools you used and how, for transparency and your own learning. In this class: the AI Documentation Template.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A form with fields to fill in: tool, prompts, what AI did, what I did.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "My AI Documentation shows I used Gemini for brainstorming and Claude for feedback — both ways the AI helped me think."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>ஆவணப்படுத்தல்</td><td>प्रलेखन / डाक्यूमेंटेशन</td><td>documentation</td><td>기록 / 문서화</td><td>記録・文書化</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Critical evaluation</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Carefully examining a source's reliability — not accepting at face value, not rejecting without examination. The OPVL move in action.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A magnifying glass over a document.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Critical evaluation of the AI source revealed that the cited 'study' didn't actually exist."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>ஆழ்ந்த மதிப்பீடு</td><td>आलोचनात्मक मूल्यांकन</td><td>évaluation critique</td><td>비판적 평가</td><td>批判的評価</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h2 id="u1">Unit 1 — Earth in the Universe + Earth as a System <span style="font-weight:400;color:var(--muted);font-size:14px;">(15 terms)</span></h2>

<h3>Habitability</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> The conditions a planet has that allow life as we know it. NOT the same as "has life" — many habitable planets may not have life.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A checklist of conditions (water, atmosphere, temperature, etc.) with checkmarks.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Earth and Mars both meet some habitability criteria; Earth has all of them, Mars has lost most."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>வாழ்வுக்கு உகந்த தன்மை</td><td>वासयोग्यता</td><td>habitabilité</td><td>거주 가능성</td><td>居住可能性</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Habitable zone (Goldilocks zone)</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> The orbital distance from a star where a planet could have liquid water at its surface. Named after the fairy-tale principle: not too hot, not too cold.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A star at center with a ring around it labeled "habitable" — Earth inside, Mars at edge, Venus inside (too hot).</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Kepler-22 b sits in the habitable zone of a Sun-like star — but its size suggests it may not be rocky."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>வாழ்வுக்கு உகந்த மண்டலம் (Goldilocks zone)</td><td>वासयोग्य क्षेत्र (Goldilocks zone)</td><td>zone habitable</td><td>거주 가능 영역 (골디락스 존)</td><td>ハビタブルゾーン（生命居住可能領域）</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Astronomical Unit (AU)</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Distance from Earth to the Sun = 149.6 million km. Used as the standard unit for measuring solar-system distances.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A line from the Sun to Earth labeled "1 AU."</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Mars orbits at 1.5 AU; the outer planets are 5–30 AU away."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>வானியல் அலகு (AU)</td><td>खगोलीय इकाई (AU)</td><td>unité astronomique (UA)</td><td>천문 단위 (AU)</td><td>天文単位（AU）</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Light-year</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Distance light travels in one Earth year = ~9.5 trillion km. Used for interstellar distances.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A beam of light with "1 year" written along it.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Proxima Centauri b is 4.2 light-years away — the closest known exoplanet."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>ஒளி-ஆண்டு</td><td>प्रकाश-वर्ष</td><td>année-lumière</td><td>광년</td><td>光年</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Exoplanet</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A planet orbiting a star other than our Sun. Over 5,000 confirmed so far.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A small planet next to a star, labeled with a name like Kepler-22b.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "TRAPPIST-1 e is an exoplanet roughly Earth-sized in the habitable zone of an M-dwarf star."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>புற-கிரகம் / எக்ஸோபிளானெட்</td><td>बहिग्र्रह / एक्सोप्लैनेट</td><td>exoplanète</td><td>외계행성</td><td>系外惑星</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Transit (detection)</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> How we detect many exoplanets — when a planet passes in front of its star, the star's brightness dips briefly.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A star's brightness curve over time with a small dip in the middle.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Kepler's transit method discovered thousands of exoplanets by watching for these brightness dips."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>தாண்டல் (transit)</td><td>पारगमन / ट्रांज़िट</td><td>transit (méthode de détection)</td><td>통과 (transit) 방법</td><td>トランジット法</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Atmosphere</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> The layer of gases surrounding a planet. Provides protection, regulates temperature, allows certain forms of life.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A planet with a translucent gas envelope around it.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Earth's atmosphere is ~78% nitrogen and 21% oxygen; Mars's is mostly CO₂ but very thin."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>வளிமண்டலம்</td><td>वायुमण्डल</td><td>atmosphère</td><td>대기</td><td>大気</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Magnetic field</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A planet's invisible force field generated by liquid iron in its core. Deflects solar wind and protects the atmosphere.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> Curved field lines coming out of a planet's poles, deflecting incoming particles.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Mars lost its magnetic field ~4 billion years ago, leading to atmospheric loss."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>காந்தப்புலம்</td><td>चुम्बकीय क्षेत्र</td><td>champ magnétique</td><td>자기장</td><td>磁場</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Subsystem (Earth)</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> One of Earth's four major systems: atmosphere, hydrosphere, geosphere, biosphere. They interact constantly.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> Four circles labeled A/H/G/B, connected by arrows showing interactions.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "Changes in one Earth subsystem propagate to the others — climate change affects hydrology affects ecosystems."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>துணை அமைப்பு / Earth subsystem</td><td>उप-तंत्र / Earth subsystem</td><td>sous-système (terrestre)</td><td>지구 하위 시스템 (subsystem)</td><td>地球サブシステム</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Feedback loop</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A cycle where the output of a process affects the process itself. Positive = amplifying; negative = stabilizing.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A circle of arrows with a + or − sign showing whether it amplifies or dampens.</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "The ice-albedo feedback loop is positive: melting ice exposes darker ocean, which absorbs more heat, melting more ice."</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Tamil</th><th>Hindi</th><th>Français</th><th>Korean</th><th>Japanese</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>உள்ளீடு / உருண்டை சுழற்சி (feedback loop)</td><td>प्रतिपुष्टि लूप</td><td>boucle de rétroaction</td><td>피드백 루프</td><td>フィードバックループ</td></tr></tbody>
</table>

<h3>Climate (vs. weather)</h3>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Long-term average weather conditions in a region. Weather is what's happening today; climate is what to expect over decades.</p>
<p><strong>Visual cue:</strong> A timeline with daily weather (short bars) and overall climate (long average line).</p>
<p><strong>In a sentence:</strong> "One hot day is weather; consistently hotter summers over 30 years is climate change."</p>
